  "prompt": "What is the relation between phase and line voltage?",
  "response": "In a three-phase power system, the relationship between phase and line voltage depends on the type of connection (delta or wye/star). Here's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. In a Wye (Star) Connection:\n- Line voltage = \u221a3 \u00d7 Phase voltage\n- Line voltage = 1.732 \u00d7 Phase voltage\n- Phase voltage = Line voltage \u00f7 \u221a3\n\n2. In a Delta Connection:\n- Line voltage = Phase voltage\n- Line voltage = Phase voltage\n\nKey points:\n- Wye connection: Line voltage is \u221a3 times the phase voltage\n- Delta connection: Line voltage equals phase voltage\n- Line voltage always refers to voltage between lines\n- Phase voltage refers to voltage across individual phase windings\n\nIn mathematical terms:\nVline = \u221a3 \u00d7 Vphase (Wye connection)\nVline = Vphase (Delta connection)\n\nThis relationship is crucial in electrical power systems for understanding voltage transformations and power distribution.",
